   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b1f903ed",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Video 2: Vectorisation\n",
    "\n",
    "Vectorisation is useful when you do not want to run `for` loops"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "047db94a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "data_file.describe"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3833af5e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "To see how many of the rows or entries in the data file are such that the seating class of the passenger is First Class.\n",
    "\n",
    "Why do I want to do this? \n",
    "In this above summary of the set, the number of entries for which the Cabin is non-null is 204. By overlooking the data file head and tail, I noticed that the Cabin is available only for the passengers who are travelling first class. To check this theory, I want to find out the above number."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "de9e2560",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "passenger_class = data_file['Pclass']\n",
    "passenger_class1 = passenger_class[passenger_class==1]\n",
    "print(len(passenger_class1))\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "54e3cb89",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "So, conclusion is that the number of passenger that are travelling first class is 216, and the number of people for whom the seating is insdie a cabin is 204. So, there are people who bought the first class still tickets and still did not take cabin. there are (216-204=) 12 such passengers who bought first class ticket but did not take the cabin. They might have sat in the lounge or they might be accompanying another person (friend/family/colleague, etc.) who has bought the cabin."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "9b93c03b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## To see all the column header names\n",
    "data_file.columns"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "19e70b9c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Computing the fare per person\n",
    "\n",
    "The `data_file` has the total fare for the person who purchased the ticket. this person might have co-passengers like family going along. The total fare is in the column `Fare`. There are two other columns that show how many co-passengers are there. The first of these 2 columns is `SibSp`, which indicates that the sibling or spouse of the person who booked the ticket is travelling alongwith them. The second column is called `Parch` and this indicates that the Parent or Child of the person who booked the ticket is travelling alongwith them."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "a7904646",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import time"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "fd1580df",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "## We will first take a subset of the data frame such that the new data frame\n",
    "# has only the three columns that are of interest to us.\n",
    "\n",
    "data_file_subset = data_file[['Fare','SibSp','Parch']]\n",
    "print(data_file_subset.shape)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Now, we will drop all the NA values from the above dataset\n",
    "data_file_subset = data_file_subset.dropna()\n",
    "print(data_file_subset)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Note: the dimensions after dropping the NA value is still the same as before\n",
    "# dropping them, which is 891 rows and 3 columns. This means there were no NAs\n",
    "# in this part of the dataset. \n",
    "\n",
    "data_file_subset.info()\n",
    "\n",
    "# Testing indexing\n",
    "a = data_file_subset.loc[1,'Fare']\n",
    "print(a)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "25230f4f",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# We will first compute the fare per person using the `for` loop code.\n",
    "# Counting with a `for` loop\n",
    "loop_start_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "\n",
    "n_row = len(data_file_subset)\n",
    "print(n_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "fare_per_person = []\n",
    "\n",
    "for counter in range(n_row):\n",
    "    total_passengers_per_row = data_file_subset.loc[counter,'SibSp'] + data_file_subset.loc[counter,'Parch'] + 1\n",
    "    fare_per_person.append(data_file_subset.loc[counter,'Fare'] / total_passengers_per_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "# fare_per_person[:10]\n",
    "\n",
    "data_file_subset['Fare_per_person'] = fare_per_person\n",
    "# data_file.head(2)\n",
    "\n",
    "loop_end_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "\n",
    "loop_duration = loop_end_time - loop_start_time\n",
    "print(f\"Time taken to compute fare per person using a `for` loop: {loop_duration} seconds\")\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "5ff1bc1d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Method 2: Computation of fare per person using vectorized operations\n",
    "vectorized_start_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "\n",
    "data_file_subset['Family_size'] = data_file_subset['SibSp'] + data_file_subset['Parch'] + 1\n",
    "data_file_subset['Fare_per_person_vectorized'] = data_file_subset['Fare'] / data_file_subset['Family_size']\n",
    "\n",
    "vectorized_end_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "\n",
    "vectorized_duration = vectorized_end_time - vectorized_start_time\n",
    "print(f\"Time taken to compute fare per person using vectorized operations: {vectorized_duration} seconds\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "46c04971",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Scaling up the data file to see the effect of the two methods on a larger\n",
    "# dataset\n",
    "df_large = pd.concat([data_file_subset]*100, ignore_index=True)\n",
    "df_large.shape\n",
    "\n",
    "# loop large\n",
    "\n",
    "loop_large_start_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "n_row_large = len(df_large)\n",
    "\n",
    "fare_per_person_large = []\n",
    "for counter in range(n_row_large):\n",
    "    total_passengers_per_row = 1 + df_large.loc[counter,'SibSp'] + df_large.loc[counter,'Parch']\n",
    "    fare_per_person_large.append(df_large.loc[counter,'Fare'] / total_passengers_per_row)\n",
    "\n",
    "df_large['Fare_per_person_loop_large'] = fare_per_person_large\n",
    "\n",
    "loop_large_end_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "loop_large_duration = loop_large_end_time - loop_large_start_time\n",
    "print(f\"Time taken to compute fare per person using a `for` loop on a large dataset: {loop_large_duration} seconds\")\n",
    "\n",
    "# vectorized large\n",
    "vectorized_large_start_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "\n",
    "df_large['Family_size'] = df_large['SibSp'] + df_large['Parch'] + 1\n",
    "df_large['Fare_per_person_vectorized_large'] = df_large['Fare'] / df_large['Family_size']\n",
    "\n",
    "vectorized_large_end_time = time.perf_counter()\n",
    "vectorized_large_duration = vectorized_large_end_time - vectorized_large_start_time\n",
    "print(f\"Time taken to compute fare per person using vectorized operations on a large dataset: {vectorized_large_duration} seconds\")\n",
    "\n",
    "speedup_factor = loop_large_duration / vectorized_large_duration\n",
    "print(f\"Speedup factor of vectorized operations over `for` loop on a large dataset: {speedup_factor} times faster\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "c7d6d33a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Video 3 Indexing\n",
    "\n",
    "Just like VLOOKUPs in Excel, however, this is way better!"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "9e51d7f4",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import pandas as pd"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "8dd1b479",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Accessing or slicing a single row using `iloc`\n",
    "\n",
    "# Note: iloc is an integer position based indexing. If you access a series of\n",
    "# rows with this, like 3:8, then the row with index 8 will not be present in\n",
    "# this slice that you made.\n",
    "row_5 = data_file.iloc[4]\n",
    "print(row_5)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "5a47dd4b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Accessing or slicing multiple rows using `iloc` (end is exclusive)\n",
    "\n",
    "row_3_to_5 = data_file.iloc[2:5]\n",
    "print(row_3_to_5)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "072f3ef2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Slicing a row and a column using `iloc` \n",
    "row_3_col_6 = data_file.iloc[2,5]\n",
    "print(row_3_col_6)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "0da987fa",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
